      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":12,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury - Plantar Fasciitis Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":8,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":10,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"Every run stays at easy pace using Daniels-Gilbert zones: 5:25 to 6:12 per km. Cap each session at 20 minutes. Walk breaks are mandatory any time foot discomfort appears, even mild. Three runs per week with at least one rest day between each. Long run Saturday is kept to the same 20-minute cap for now. The goal here is tissue tolerance, not fitness. Week 4 is a deload: drop total distance by roughly 20% and keep effort easy. Do not chase the upper end of the easy pace range. Stay toward 6:00 to 6:12 per km to protect the plantar fascia.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":11,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":14,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90/10 easy/cross-train\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"notes\":\"Volume increases gradually, staying within 10% per week. The 20-minute cap per run lifts only when your physiotherapist explicitly clears longer efforts. Until then, a fourth session may be added as optional low-impact cross-training such as cycling or pool running, not counted toward running volume. Easy pace target is 5:45 to 6:12 per km using Daniels-Gilbert zones. No tempo, no intervals, no speed work of any kind. Week 8 is a deload: return to week 5 volume. Walk breaks remain available whenever foot discomfort appears. If pain returns at any point, drop back to Phase 1 protocol immediately.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":15,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85/15 easy/moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":349,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":349,\"notes\":\"This phase assumes physiotherapist clearance to extend run duration beyond 20 minutes. Do not enter this phase without that clearance. The Saturday long run begins to extend, reaching 30 to 35 minutes by week 10. All running remains easy pace using Daniels-Gilbert zones: 5:25 to 6:12 per km. Moderate label here means the long run is slightly longer, not faster. No speed work. Week 11 is a lighter week before the final recovery phase. Any return of plantar fasciitis symptoms is a signal to stop and consult your physiotherapist before continuing.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":10,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":10,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"Final week consolidates the rebuild. Three short easy runs, no pressure on distance or pace. Use this week to assess how the foot has responded to the full 12 weeks. This is the right time to schedule a physiotherapist review before planning any return to structured training or racing. The pace-zone index of 46.5 reflects your pre-injury fitness. Current fitness is likely 5 to 10 percent lower after the layoff. A reassessment after this week will give a cleaner picture of where you actually are.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"This plan is built around one constraint above all others: active plantar fasciitis with physiotherapist clearance for 20-minute easy runs only. The pace-zone index of 46.5 derived from your pre-injury 44:00 10K sets the pace targets via Daniels-Gilbert zones, but those targets are a ceiling, not a mandate. Easy pace of 5:25 to 6:12 per km applies throughout. The lower end of that range, toward 6:00 to 6:12, is the right target for the first eight weeks. Plantar fasciitis responds poorly to load spikes. The first four weeks prioritize tissue tolerance over fitness. Volume starts at 8 km per week across three runs. That is a modest step up from your recent 6.1 km week, which itself was a step back from 8.5 km. The build is deliberate and slow. Deload weeks at weeks 4 and 8 are not optional. They are the mechanism that lets the plantar fascia adapt without accumulating stress. No speed work appears anywhere in this plan. Threshold, interval, repetition, and fast-repetition paces from Daniels-Gilbert zones are present in your profile for reference but are not used here. Reintroducing intensity before the foot is fully tolerant of easy volume is how returning injuries become chronic ones. The transition to longer runs in weeks 9 to 11 is conditional on physiotherapist clearance. If that clearance does not come, Phase 3 reverts to the Phase 2 structure. Three days per week is respected throughout. That frequency is appropriate for a return-from-injury context and matches your stated preference.\",\"warnings\":\"You have active plantar fasciitis with a physiotherapist clearance limited to 20-minute easy runs with walk breaks if any foot pain occurs. This plan is built within those constraints. Do not progress to Phase 3 or extend run duration beyond 20 minutes without explicit clearance from your physiotherapist. Any return of sharp heel pain, morning foot stiffness that worsens over consecutive days, or pain that persists into the run after a warm-up walk break is a signal to stop running and contact your physiotherapist before your next session. Do not redistribute missed sessions or mileage to other days. A missed run is a missed run. Attempting to catch up adds load that the plantar fascia has not been prepared for. Your pre-injury pace-zone index of 46.5 is a useful baseline but does not reflect your current fitness after the injury layoff. Expect early runs to feel easier than the paces suggest. That is appropriate. Fitness will return faster than tissue tolerance, so do not let easier perceived effort become a reason to push harder or longer.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
